ome characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Rixton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Long Riston (East Yorkshire), North and South Reston (Lincolnshire), and East and Sco Ruston (Norfolk). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hrīs</i> ‘brushwood’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The name may sometimes have been confused with   Ritson  .","English: occasional variant of   Rushton  .","Scottish: habitational name from Reston in Coldingham (Berwickshire), cognate with 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Ritson","meanings":["English:","variant of <b>Richson</b>, a shortened form of   Richardson  . The name may sometimes have been confused with or assimilated to   Rushton  .","in southern England perhaps a habitational name from Ritson, in Halwell (Devon)."]}]},{"name":"Isabelle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabel","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabelle de Rixton was born in 1360, in Rixton, Lancashire, England, her father, Matthew de Rixton, was 40 and her mother, Isabel, was 40. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with John de Towneley. She died after 1386, in Burnley, Lancashire, England."},"et":{"1360–after 1386":"1360–pärast 1386","1360–1386":"1360–1386","1358–1399":"1358–1399","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1387–1454":"1387–1454","–Female":"Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1320–1397":"1320–1397","1358":"1358","1454":"1454","1399":"1399","1387":"1387","1342":"1342","1397":"1397","1320":"1320","1386":"1386","1385":"1385","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","after 1386":"pärast 1386","Burnley, Lancashire, England":"Burnley, Lancashire, England","Rixton with Glazebrook, Lancashire, England":"Rixton, Lancashire, England","Towneley, Lanc, Eng":"Towneley, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1360–after 1386":"1360–1386 jälkeen","1360–1386":"1360–1386","1358–1399":"1358–1399","1385–Female":"1385–Kuollut","1387–1454":"1387–1454","–Female":"Kuollut","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1320–1397":"1320–1397","1358":"1358","1454":"1454","1399":"1399","1387":"1387","1342":"1342","1397":"1397","1320":"1320","1386":"1386","1385":"1385","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","after 1386":"1386 jälkeen","Burnley, Lancashi